== What makes SaaS different?
Software as a Service business is a very interesting model. As it is in most of the case a subscription based system, you are not forced to sell to new customers but can focus on building a great product for your existing customers.

Another highly fascinating thing about SaaS Apps is, that they are essentially no costs. Of course, you need people to build it, make it better and scale it, but that is cheap in comparison to what costs you have in other businesses, where you need to buy expensive special vehicles, materials or tools. As the term says it, you are in the service business and a highly and cost-efficient scaling one, too.

And as software is your service, sure you have a certain set of features but every software is unique at the end of the day and you can't (and most people won't) compare the list of features from one App to the other. Most likely you have a feature no other competitor offers while they have features, you don't need or want to have. Which makes your customers, your customers and you always want to convince them with a different argument than "being cheaper" – your competitors, too, by the way.

Running a software in this business means, you are not bound to competitive pricing or have any numbers running the business for you. Setting the price for a software as a service offer is a total psychology game. But one of high importance as it is a key factor whether people can and want to buy (or effort) it. The beauty of it though, once you've find your target, it's gonna sell like hot cakes. And on top, you have basically no costs with upselling either. We'll come back to that a little later.


