== Basic Principles of Pricing psychology

Software as a service product have a few spins to it, a few I've just mentioned before. Another one that comes with it, it the ability to repackage it into any kind of size for basically no extra costs. You can sell the same thing just in three or four different sizes. Thus allowing you to have an offer for each budget size.

And there we've already found one key instrument: have multiple tiers. To give the options and let the customer think about what they want. But be careful to give only a few. Giving too many options because a lot to read, compare and in the end too hard to decide – a fundamental problem with crowd funding pricing. These tiers should be viewable in one page, their differences and benefits clearly distinguishable. I have the best experiences with setting three pricing levels - some argue it's five, but I often feel that is too much to read (as you need five clear differentiations).

As said, pricing an SaaS is mostly psychology and the counter part is the customer.   

=== How low can you go?
The lowest of the tiers is the one, you can use for advertising and marketing. Try to make it as low as you can think without having the feeling of selling out to cheap. This is also the (only) tier you offer the free trial on. By making it rather cheap, this has the nice additional benefit that even if people the decide to not stick with you, if the number is low, they are less likely to cancel it (as it feels it's not worth the effort). So, if you can reasonably offer your service for €9.99/month, do that.

=== Too thin
Because it is too thin anyways. The offer of that lowest pricing shouldn't be bad or cheesy, but don't forget it is your marketing-offer to get people to look into your service. Offer a service,which is "just not quiet enough". You should have an idea about, who your customer is, done some personas and research, so you know what they need. Maybe they'll run through ten clients a month, then eight are included in your tier, they are running a radio stream with music so they need 192kb/s mp3, include up to 128kb, if they have revenue of 15k per month, your tier allows up to 10k – you get the picture.

The more obvious it is this tier isn't quiet enough for them, the better, don't let scream into their face, but use terms and numbers they understand. The reason you want to do that is the following: they are checking your pricing. Which means, they are interested in your service and most likely want to use it. If they just want to try it, those numbers don't mean much and they'll hit the "free trial button" without looking into it for too long. But if they really consider, then you've already sold it, you just need to settle on the price now. By making the cheapest unusable to them, they immediately move to the second tier.

=== The second is good, the third is to settle
Now this tier offers much more than the first one we've talked about. Not only can they run their business with it but it is almost too generous, offers much more than they ever feel to be needing. For just about double the initial price (or slightly less) - very good. And that is the price range they want to and _should settle_. But by offering so much already, all they ever wanted, they become curious about what more you could be offering. And they look at the third and compare it to the second.

Now here it becomes interesting. By increasing the price slightly but adding something extra-ordinary - even if they don't necessarily need it - they become very interested. Because there is so much more in there in comparison to what is in tier 2 but it isn't that much more expensive. So in comparison it even feels like a really good offer, you get more for your money. In my experience this is done the best by adding exactly one key thing on top. Like for the audio-stream example, add a second stream - it adds a lot but got "thrown in" rather cheap.

.The psychology behind this
NOTE: has been explained very well by link:http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xOhb4LwAaJk[Dan Ariely in this youtube video]: we don't know our preferences that well and therefore are receptive to influences like supposedly good offers in comparison to another.

=== Real world case
I did exactly this pricing range for a crowd funding campaign for a Hollywood movie and though it never finished (because of internal problems), we had it in the phase of money raising. I told them to put up the following tiers:

 * 9.95 € - you were thanked on the website, got access to the bonus material and live updates through the websites about the shoot, as well as a download-link for movie as soon as it gets released on Bluray

 * 29.95 € - Same as before, but you'd also be mentioned in the credits of the movie.

 * 49.95 € - Aside from the news updates, being mentioned in the credits, you'd also be receiving a real disc version of the Bluray.

This allowed the studio to advertise with "support this movie starting from 9.95€". But the real deal was, getting mentioned in the movie, so people were immediately checking the second higher tier as the first didn't offer this. And though many settled on this, for less than double the price, you'd also receive a Bluray - well, doesn't that sound great?

So, thought 57% of the people (another 21% went for the first and 22% for the second). We sold them a Bluray disc for 20€. A movie - not a DVD-set. A movie they already have access through a download link to. A Bluray discs, which costs essentially nothing in product (why they wanted to offer it as part of the lowest pricing range initially). We wouldn't have gotten anyone to pay for this, if I had said it this way. But through this pricing schema, we could. And they were happy to do so.

.This is a kickstarter like campaign
[NOTE]
====
Given, this is not a reoccurring subscription but a fan-driven one-time transaction also selling the fact, that you are taking part in getting something done that without you wouldn't happen, so people are generally more generous.

But using a similar pricing scheme with 19.90€, 29.90€ and 39.90€ would probably have the same effect on a subscription basis.
====

=== Ending with the Nine
I've very bluntly ignored the discussing of the pricing numbers and given you cases that all end with the number 9. If you are at least a little familiar with the subject, you should be very aware that we don't exactly know why, but having the price end with a nine outsells every other option (with 5 and 7 right behind but off by far). This has been shown in a series of studies, like link:http://link.springer.com/article/10.1023%2FA%3A1023581927405[this one from MIT] and discussed in detail in books like link:http://www.amazon.com/dp/080909469X/ref=cm_sw_su_dp["Priceless" by William Poundstone] footnote:[Published at Hill and Wang, 2011, ISBN 978-0809094691] so I won't get into detail on this again.

=== Enterprise ain't part of this
This all only applies, if your customers are mainly end-consumers and small- and mid-size companies but not for enterprise. The basic rule goes like this: if the company is big enough to have someone, who's job is it to mainly buy this kinda stuff, they'll call you up and ask to negotiate a custom pricing tier with you. And even if that is only to justify the existence of their job (as they have work to do: negotiate with you), they'll do it.

But as this costs extra effort on your side in comparison to auto-serviced customers, don't forget to charge them for it, too. Aside from your three tiers, you add another box on the bottom saying you are open to discuss further models and individual pricing for bigger customers or special areas (like non-profits or education, like Google is doing). And that negotiation you go from 2 simultaneous stream to 10 and add a big support package on top, that you sell for at least ten times the highest price you have on your tiers. That at least puts it back into the price-range that enterprise is used to and happy talk about: they really rather buy the service for 5k€ than for 50€ as the later is harder to justify.

That is also why even your highest priced tier should have some limits you can sell to enterprise and high-class customers - otherwise you'd nothing to sell them. And even if they eventually settle for eight times the highest tier so they feel they negotiated stuff out of you, it was worth the effort for you. But don't ever think that this is an option to include via one-click sign-up. Enterprise won't do one-click-sign-up of it anyways.


