== Upselling without Upsetting
I talked about the beauty of upselling within SaaS-Product before a little. The greatest thing is, what you upsell often doesn't cost you any more anyway. And though a good pricing strategy on the overview page we've discussed before, can already get the people into getting the more expensive tier, there is more you can upsell with. Sadly, upselling has been abused in the past, like airlines tricking you into getting a "travel insurance" by already checking the field for you. To some it has a bad taste to it and why not, that behavior is pretty upsetting to anyone. Which is really not the first experience you want to make starting to do business with them. Understand that the upsell is still part of the first experience chain and getting this right is important.

One company that gets upselling very right is Apple. Like everything in this chain, this also is a question of the communication and ways to present it to the other party, which decides whether it works or not. And though Apple sells end-consumer hardware, the same principles still apply to the upsell of SaaS product during the initial checkout. Let's see how they do it.

=== Case Study: Upselling like Apple
When you go to the Apple online store to buy a new MacBook Air (as an example), you are presented with different models, similar to our packages or tiers from before:

.Selecting a Macbook Air
image::image/page-1-above-fold.png[A Screenshot of the Macbook Air Selection]


Same as we discussed for our tiers, there are just a few things different in these tiers, that make for a big distinction: the first being the Screen size (either 11 inch or 13) and the secondary being the flash storage. By presenting those very blunt, Apple makes the question which one to buy not about the price but first about the screen size — which they do very clever by having the second screen even be presented bigger — and in the secondary stage about the storage. First you pick the screen size, then the storage and then you are presented with the price. The price in this way is merely a result of our decisions and wasn't part of the decision in the first place. 

And now that you've decided what you want, you don't really care that Apple is selling you 128GB of storage for 200EUR extra anymore. But it gets even better once you are selecting this one. Because then Apple presents you with the "configuration page", a second page to actually upsell you even more.

.The "configuration" page
image::image/apple-store-page-2.png[The configuration screen]

Sure, you can actually configure the CPU, memory and keyboard in here (which you probably want to do actually) but there is plenty of things listed, which are actually about selling you more things: how is an external screen, an AppleTV or a Printer part of a MacBook Air configuration? Well, it isn't.

But by having this second "configuration"-screen, Apple does something very smart here. It took the decision of which general package you picked out of the scope. That has already been decided, the other options aren't presented anymore. And by splitting this into two pages, you don't have to bother about comparing prices of the configuration to other packages anymore. Adding 8GB of RAM on a 13-inch could potentially cost more than on the 11-inch (which could even have plausible, technical reasons), but no costumer would actually go back and check. Because picking another basic package isn't of any question anymore.

Another thing you've hopefully noticed is the way this is presented: Apple takes four-fifth of the width to focus on the configuration. The summary of what you've selected on the other hand is just a tiny part on the right. And though it is showing the total price, always stays with the user and as such gives them total transparency about their choices, by keeping it to the top right, we are less likely to look at it or at least not until we've scrolled down the main part totally already.

By also splitting them into big chunks that basically cover the bigger part of your screen while you scroll over them, each upgrade becomes separate from the others, making them appear as individual, not too expensive choices. And I have to actively decide on each one, that I don't want them though it is only 29,99€. And by keeping them separate, the decision I just made for the thunderbolt cable has nothing to do with the mini-display-port-cable I am looking at right now. Look it's only 29,99€. In the customers brain the other decision has been done and labeled as such, so just because I want the mini-display-port, the customer would probably not go back and change his mind on items before in the list.

.Default is "None"
[NOTE]
====
One major flaw that many (airlines) do, is preselecting upsell-options and forcing the user to actively remove the selection in an often complicated way. Tricking a customer into upselling is an obvious way to have more people upsell but makes the customer angry and educates the user you aren't a trustworthy party.

Unlike how Apple is doing it here, making it clear you don't get tricked into buying anything you don't want by communicating: "It is your choice. We are happy either way. We just think this might be of interest to you, too." And the customer listens. And they buy. And they are happy about it.
====

==== The upsell
Let's take a look at the individual things Apple tries to sell here. The same as on a normal product page, it needs to be selling the user, so it looks good, is interesting and gets quite some space. By giving upselling so much room, Apple has enough space to present the product and all important information and list the options. Just scrolling over them is going to take a little and at least one is going to catch your eye.

And once again, how they present it, is of high importance. Let's take this external storage as an example:

.Upselling you the Thunderbold storage
image::image/page-2-storage-none.png[Thunderbold Storage]

Not only does it have quite some room and scrolling over it takes long enough for our eye to catch and the brain to notice the content, but also the way of decision making is again like before. By presenting the price in square brackets it appears to be merely a consequence of the decision but not really part of it. No, the details of option to select are in foreground. And it gets better, because Apple isn't done upselling once you selected one option:

.After selecting an option, the price disappears
image::image/page-2-storage-selected.png[Selected a Storage]

Did you notice the difference? Apple changed the prices. As I have decided on an Option, not only does it become part of my decision (and the summary) so the price disappears, also the other prices are updated to only show the difference in pricing. Genius. Not only because now the more expensive options don't appear to be as expensive any more but also because by phrasing it "Subtract 349,95€", even the "None" option now appears to be costing something triggered by providing a positive number. Our brain immediately notices that as high, and it takes a while before it processed that "subtract" needs we have to negate it. 

And though thinking of the negative is something our brain generally can't do, by using words here this also requires other parts of the brain to process it. It would be quite different if instead of "subtract", it would show the minus sign or – even worse – color-code the values red and green, things our brain would understand immediately. But this subtle way of saying it, the brain needs to process much more information and in different parts and given the size of those numbers aren't that big, we don't think it is very important to do that. Making it more likely to stick with the selection or even chose another one that feels less expensive now. Again, Apple changed the conversation and moved it behind the question whether you take this or not and towards whether you want to take more instead.

=== What to upsell
In order to be able to upsell, you need to know your numbers. You should know them inside out anyway but especially those things, people think they need or want and which are slightly outside the scope of the main product, are of interest here. The examples mentioned before still apply here, so for example buying an upgrade to stream 256kb/s instead of just up to 192kb/s on a radio stream. Or even offering 320kb/s as the ultimate upgrade, so that DJs are super happy to be able to offer the best quality though the actual effect for most listeners wouldn't actually change after 192kb/s anyway.

Upsell is always the question of what you need, want and might want to need. Like in the Apple example, selling video adapters and printers just makes a lot of sense. Because I am buying the laptop with specific needs in mind. And by showing me those options I am reminded that I actually want to show presentations at conferences with it so I need an adapter. 

Another example that comes from the radio service I was mentioning before, is about one specific feature, which actually costs them nothing and was a default for long time but is something very easy and cheap to upsell with: stream to shoutcast service. Shoutcast is an external server that would then handle the distribution of the streams meaning that only one stream out is needed at any time as the distribution would be handed off to a third party. Enabling this feature would be classic thing to upsell with. Not only because more people think they need it than actually ever will use it but also as the numbers show plenty people actually do use it instead of taking the more expensive tier with more streams.

By having to buy this feature extra on the second page, people are very likely to be willing to pay a higher total than just getting a tier that costs more but includes more streams and would cover them. People pay for control and convenience.

